ment policies and processes for land use and protection do not always reflect the needs and values of local residents. Instead, the resulting landscapes produced by the NPS represent a series of compromises between use and protection—and between the area’s historic pastoral character and a newer vision of wilderness. A fascinating and deeply researched book, The Paradox of Preservation will appeal to those studying environmental history, conservation, public lands, and cultural landscape management, and to those looking to learn more about the history of this dynamic California coastal region.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aNatural resources conservation areaszCaliforniazPoint Reyes PeninsulaxManagement. 0aNatural resources conservation areaszCaliforniazPoint ReyesPeninsulaxManagement. 7aSCIENCE / Environmental Science (see also Chemistry / Environmental).2bisacsh  a1960s.  aacademic.  acalifornia coast.  acalifornia.  acoastal region.  acompromise.  aculture.  adairy farming.  adrakes oyster bay company.  afishing.  aland management.  alandscape.  alocal business.  alocals.  amanagement.  anational park service.  anational park.  anational seashore.  anps.  aoyster farming.  apoint reyes.  aprotection.  apublic lands.  aranching.  aresearch.  aresidents.  aseaside.  asmall business.  awilderness.1 aLowenthal, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831106675470 cprintz978052027707640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780520966420?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520966420423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520966420/original  a978-3-11-066754-7  University of C